section.t:
Typical GEO-satellite based systems exhibit specific characteristics that can be harmful for a data-center that is tuned for a majority of use-cases. Among the main network-level impacts, we can note:
		A large propagation delay of at least 250ms one-way delay;
		A high bit-rate in case of mobile users or when a user connects behind a box using Wi-Fi;
		Asymmetric links.

These characteristics have an impact on end-to-end congestion controls:
		Transport initialization: the 3-way handshake takes a long time reducing the time at which actual data can be transmitted;
		Maximum windows sizing: to fully exploit the bottleneck capacity, the high BDP may induce an important number of in-flights packets;
		Reliability: packet losses detection and correction is slow and the time needed for the end server to react to a congestion event may not be relevant;
		Getting up to speed: the exponential increase of the data rate transmission for a channel capacity probing is slowed down when the RTT is high.

A new extension named "BDP_data" is defined for NewSessionTicket. It contains the following value: BDP_value, that is the value in in bits per second (same unit as ). The reception of the field BDP_data provides the client with 3 indications:
		The path with this server has a large BDP;
		The server added the path characteristics in the opaque 'ticket' field;
		The server will optimize the reopening of the session upon reception of this opaque ticket.
